stories: Molecular graphs represent chemical reactions in retrosynthetic analysis of compound (cs) libraries, whose prediction and property analysis are crucial indicators for molecular design. Nevertheless, challenges associated with quality and availability of data as well as the complexity of chemical transformations of interest have hindered an automatic and bespoke analysis framework, often still relying (in part) on human intuition and validation. We introduce a reaction extraction framework for molecular graphs, built from unsupervised, clustering-based machine learning methods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification of chemical properties of the former. thereby, the need for human expertise or large training datasets to inform predictive models is circumvented, while additionally enabling the automation of atomwise property and reaction labeling. In particular, we demonstrate that retrosynthetic planning can be conducted effectively, efficiently and without any training data as a direct result of this approach.

Biological pathways visualize metabolic reactions in systems biology analysis of genomic libraries, whose prediction and pathway analysis are vital indicators for therapeutic design. However, challenges associated with quality and availability of data as well as the complexity of biological processes of interest have hindered an automatic and bespoke analysis framework, often still relying (in part) on human intuition and validation. We introduce a pathway extraction framework for biological graphs, built from unsupervised, clustering-based machine learning methods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification of biological properties of the former. thereby, the need for human expertise or large training datasets to inform predictive models is circumvented, while additionally enabling the automation of gene-wise property and reaction labeling. In particular, we demonstrate that pathway planning can be conducted effectively, efficiently and without any training data as a direct result of this approach.
